20exhibition%20is%20a%20part%20of%20the%20larger%20%E2%80%98Ancient%20World%20Project%E2%80%99%20of%20CSMVS%2C%20which%20was%20meant%20to%20commemorate%2075%20Years%20of%20Indian%20independence.%20The%20goal%20is%20to%20bring%20works%20of%20art%20from%20other%20cultures%20to%20Mumbai%20to%20enrich%20the%20understanding%20of%20a%20shared%20human%20history.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EEspousing%20an%20exceptional%20narrative%2C%20this%20is%20one%20of%20the%20few%20exhibitions%20which%20has%20used%20ancient%20sculptures%20as%20historical%20evidence%20to%20determine%20cultural%20connections%20between%20different%20ancient%20civilisations.%20By%20underscoring%20the%20ritual%2C%20architectural%20and%20philosophical%20meanings%20behind%20these%20sculptures%2C%20the%20exhibition%20emphasises%20India%E2%80%99s%20centrality%20in%20the%20ancient%20world%2C%20rather%20than%20merely%20placing%20Indian%20art%20in%20comparison%20with%20the%20classical%20cultures%20of%20Greece%20and%20Rome%2C%20as%20is%20often%20done.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMost%20significantly%2C%20for%20the%20first%20time%2C%20we%20see%20a%20shift%20in%20curatorial%20perspective.%20The%20exhibition%20has%20been%20conceptualised%20with%20Indian%20museum%20visitors%20in%20mind%2C%20many%20of%20whom%20might%20never%20have%20the%20opportunity%20to%20travel.%20The%20goal%20is%20to%20provide%20them%20with%20the%20chance%20to%20experience%20the%20art%20and%20culture%20of%20other%20parts%20of%20the%20world%2C%20and%20to%20open%20up%20new%20ways%20of%20viewing%20their%20own%20culture%20through%20its%20relation%20to%20other%20societies.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EEncouraging%20the%20Indian%20audiences%20to%20engage%20with%20these%20ancient%20sculptures%2C%20ask%20questions%20relevant%20to%20them%20and%20interpret%20the%20objects%20from%20their%20own%20cultural%20understanding%20could%20unveil%20a%20multitude%20of%20meanings%20within%20these%20museum%20artifacts.%20A%20second%20objective%20of%20the%20exhibition%20is%20to%20collaborate%20with%20local%20schools%20and%20universities%2C%20urging%20students%20and%20educators%20to%20expand%20their%20learning%20beyond%20the%20classroom%20and%20view%20material%20culture%20and%20museum%20collections%20as%20vital%20sources%20for%20historical%20methodology.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20study%20of%20ancient%20history%20as%20a%20discipline%20is%20still%20framed%20from%20a%20European%2F%20Mediterranean%20perspective.%20This%20process%20of%20audience%20engagement%20will%20hopefully%20encourage%20a%20new%20kind%20of%20knowledge%20tradition%20and%20also%20nudge%20historians%20towards%20writing%20more%20global%20histories%20of%20the%20ancient%20world.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3ESculptures%20in%20museums%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAcademic%20interest%20in%20India%E2%80%99s%20ancient%20sculptures%20began%20from%20about%20the%20late%2018th%20century%20when%20European%20travellers%20and%20officers%20of%20the%20English%20East%20India%20Company%20began%20to%20travel%20to%20different%20parts%20of%20the%20subcontinent%2C%20surveying%20its%20topography%20and%20people%2C%20discovering%20its%20history%20and%20documenting%20its%20architectural%20and%20archaeological%20remains.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EInitially%2C%20religious%20sculptures%20began%20to%20be%20collected%20for%20their%20fine%20craftsmanship%2C%20but%20later%20they%20became%20objects%20of%20intellectual%20curiosity.%20Given%20their%20many%20heads%2C%20multiple%20limbs%20and%20voluptuous%20bodies%2C%20they%20were%20often%20labelled%20as%20monstrous%2C%20barbaric%2C%20vulgar%20and%20irrational.%20Sculptures%20were%20initially%20shipped%20off%20to%20Britain%20as%20souvenirs%20of%20the%20empire%20where%20they%20were%20scientifically%20studied%20and%20critically%20analysed%2C%20especially%20in%20comparison%20with%20those%20from%20classical%20Greece%20and%20Rome.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhile%20the%20intellectual%20focus%20at%20the%20time%20was%20to%20collect%20Indic%20manuscripts%20and%20inscriptions%20and%20to%20translate%2C%20decipher%20and%20interpret%20these%2C%20sculptures%20were%20seen%20merely%20as%20archaeological%20artifacts%2C%20investigated%20for%20their%20aesthetic%20qualities%20and%20assessed%20for%20how%20accurately%20they%20represented%20related%20ancient%20texts.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWith%20the%20establishment%20of%20museums%20in%20India%2C%20the%20colonial%20British%20government%20decided%20to%20preserve%20India%E2%80%99s%20rich%20archaeological%20and%20ethnological%20materials%20within%20the%20country.%20The%20first%20museum%20was%20founded%20in%20Calcutta%20in%201814%2C%20known%20as%20the%20Imperial%20Museum%2C%20and%20later%20named%20as%20the%20Indian%20Museum.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMuseums%20in%20the%20subcontinent%20became%20integral%20to%20the%20orientalist%20enterprise%20of%20knowledge%20production%20regarding%20its%20Indian%20colony.%20They%20played%20a%20role%20in%20systematically%20classifying%2C%20organizing%20scientifically%2C%20and%20disseminating%20this%20knowledge%20among%20the%20Indian%20public.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EReligious%20sculptures%20became%20highly%20prized%20objects%20within%20museum%20collections%20meant%20to%20showcase%20India%E2%80%99s%20ancient%20religions%20and%20document%20its%20rich%20artistic%20heritage.%20Sculptures%20were%20neatly%20categorised%20on%20the%20bases%20of%20religious%20denomination%2C%20male%20and%20female%20attributes%2C%20the%20placement%20of%20their%20hands%20and%20feet%2C%20%3Cem%3Emudras%3C%2Fem%3E%20and%20as%20representing%20the%20dramatic%20moments%20of%20the%20mythological%20universe.%20Museum%20displays%20were%20also%20organised%20around%20the%20great%20epochs%20of%20his%C2%ADtory%20and%20dynastic%20achievements%2C%20where%20religious%20sculptures%20were%20grouped%20under%20broad%20chronological%20and%20dynastic%20labels.%20Royal%20patronage%20seemed%20to%20provide%20the%20only%20kind%20of%20explanation%20for%20the%20production%20of%20art%20with%20little%20or%20no%20lay%20participation.%20It%20is%20still%20fairly%20common%20to%20find%20sculptural%20galleries%20in%20Indian%20museums%20named%20as%20Mauryan%20art%2C%20Gupta%20art%2C%20Chola%20art%20and%20so%20on%2C%20in%20honour%20of%20the%20great%20ruling%20dynasties.%20By%20focussing%20on%20their%20aesthetics%20and%20materiality%2C%20the%20early%20museums%20set%20a%20broad%20template%20within%20which%20religious%20sculptures%20came%20to%20be%20viewed%20and%20studied%20in%20various%20academic%20disciplines.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3ESculptures%20in%20conversation%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20%E2%80%98Ancient%20Sculptures%E2%80%99%20exhibition%20is%20one%20of%20those%20rare%20instances%20which%20addresses%20many%20of%20these%20lacunas.%20Ancient%20sculptures%20are%20framed%20to%20trace%20networks%20of%20connections%20and%20exchange%20of%20knowledge%20traditions%20between%20India%20and%20the%20wider%20world%20through%20artistic%20themes%2C%20philosophies%20and%20religious%20beliefs%20without%20drawing%20civilisational%20comparisons.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EOn%20entering%20the%20imposing%20Indo-Saracenic%20building%20of%20the%20CSMVS%2C%20a%20stone%20lotus%20medallion%2C%20a%20fragment%20from%20the%20great%20Amravati%20stupa%2C%20is%20placed%20at%20the%20museum%20entrance%20to%20greet%20visitors.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20557px)%2085vw%2C%20557px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F03115558%2Fimage-1798.png%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22557%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F03115558%2Fimage-1798.png%20557w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F03115558%2Fimage-1798-230x300.png%20230w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-695501%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22725%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3ELotus%20medallion%20from%20the%20railing%20of%20the%20Buddhist%20stupa%20at%20Amravati%2C%20100-199%20CE%2C%20CSMVS%20collection.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20lotus%20is%20known%20as%20a%20symbol%20of%20peace%2C%20prosperity%2C%20purity%20and%20beauty%20in%20many%20cultures%2C%20including%20India%2C%20Egypt%20and%20China.%20The%20centrepiece%20of%20the%20exhibition%2C%20however%2C%20is%20a%20majestic%20Yajna%20Varaha%20sculpture%20from%20Vidisha%2C%20Madhya%20Pradesh%2C%20which%20is%20strategically%20placed%20under%20the%20grand%20rotunda%20of%20the%20museum.%20It%20automatically%20draws%20the%20visitors%20to%20the%20centre%20of%20the%20exhibition.%20The%20intricately%20carved%20Yajna%20Varaha%20has%20350%20images%20of%20divinities%20engraved%20on%20its%20body%20and%20Bhu%20Devi%20(Earth%20goddess)%2C%20standing%20next%20to%20it%20clinging%20to%20its%20snout.%20At%20the%20tip%20of%20its%20snout%20sits%20Saraswati%2C%20the%20goddess%20of%20knowledge%2C%20and%20images%20of%20the%20sun%20and%20moon%2C%20the%20lotus%20bud%2C%20various%20aquatic%20animals%20embellish%20the%20different%20parts%20of%20its%20body.%20The%20snake%20and%20%3Cem%3Egaruda%3C%2Fem%3E%20symbolise%20its%20association%20with%20Vishnu%2C%20and%20figures%20carved%20near%20its%20legs%20represent%20the%20cosmic%20directions.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20Varaha%20%3Cem%3Eavatara%20%3C%2Fem%3Eof%20Vishnu%20is%20the%20symbol%20of%20the%20cosmos%2C%20yet%20it%20tells%20many%20stories%2C%20such%20as%20the%20story%20of%20the%20cosmic%20%3Cem%3Eyajna%20%3C%2Fem%3E(sacrifice)%20and%20the%20myth%20of%20the%20churning%20of%20the%20ocean.%20In%20a%20similar%20fashion%2C%20the%20exhibition%20narrates%20multiple%20stories%20through%20these%20sculptures.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20984px)%2061vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2045vw%2C%20600px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F03120828%2Fimage-1799.png%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22738%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F03120828%2Fimage-1799.png%20738w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F03120828%2Fimage-1799-300x298.png%20300w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F03120828%2Fimage-1799-150x150.png%20150w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-695503%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22732%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EYajna%20Varaha%2C%20Boar%20incarnation%20of%20Vishnu%2C%20900-1099%20CE%2C%20Vidisha%20District%20Archaeological%20Museum.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESeveral%20icons%20from%20the%20Greek%2C%20Roman%20and%20Egyptian%20mythologies%20have%20been%20ingeniously%20displayed%20around%20the%20Varaha%20to%20create%20several%20strands%20of%20conversation%20between%20the%20deities%20across%20cultures.%20A%20marble%20bust%20of%20the%20Greek%20deity%20Zeus%2C%20(Jupiter%20in%20Rome)%2C%20and%20elegant%2C%20nude%20torsos%20of%20Triton%2C%20Apollo%20and%20Dionysus%20display%20the%20beauty%20of%20the%20human%20form.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20218px)%2085vw%2C%20218px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F03115332%2Fimage-1797-218x300.png%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22218%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F03115332%2Fimage-1797-218x300.png%20218w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F03115332%2Fimage-1797.png%20550w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-695500%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22300%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EGreek%20Dionysus%20or%20Roman%20Bacchus%2C%20God%20of%20intoxication%2C%20abundance.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EYet%20unlike%20traditional%20art%20historical%20scholarship%2C%20which%20overemphasises%20the%20artistic%20and%20intellectual%20superiority%20of%20the%20ancient%20Greeks%20and%20Romans%2C%20the%20exhibition%20uses%20these%20classical%20sculptures%20to%20highlight%20a%20shared%20religious%20and%20visual%20idiom%20within%20the%20Mediterranean%20cultures%20of%20Greece%20and%20Rome%2C%20but%20more%20significantly%20with%20other%20parts%20of%20the%20world%2C%20such%20as%20with%20India%20and%20Egypt.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20accompanying%20object%20descriptions%2C%20labels%20and%20wall%20texts%20include%20details%20of%20the%20original%20architectural%20and%20geographical%20locations%20of%20these%20images%2C%20thus%20highlighting%20that%20sculptures%20were%20not%20merely%20representations%20of%20beautiful%20bodies%20but%20had%20a%20religious%20and%20cultural%20purpose%2C%20and%20they%20were%20meant%20to%20be%20placed%20on%20structures%20such%20as%20temples%2C%20the%20city%20centre%2C%20gymnasiums%2C%20burial%20places%20and%20so%20on.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20exhibition%20curators%20have%20undertaken%20painstaking%20research%20to%20show%20site%20maps%20and%20multimedia%20images%20of%20temples%20and%20altars%2C%20such%20as%20the%20Greek%20Parthenon%2C%20Temple%20of%20Artemis%20and%20so%20on.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20exhibition%20also%20juxtaposes%20select%20sculptural%20masterpieces%20from%20India%20against%20Greek%2C%20Roman%20and%20Egyptian%20pieces%20to%20draw%20out%20certain%20themes%20and%20beliefs%20perceived%20as%20common%20to%20all%20ancient%20cultures%2C%20such%20the%20appreciation%20of%20the%20feminine%20form%2C%20control%20of%20river%20waters%20and%20the%20turbulent%20seas%2C%20ideas%20of%20cosmos%2C%20divine%20kingship%2C%20encounters%20with%20death%20and%20recurrent%20animal%20motifs%20in%20art.%20For%20instance%2C%20the%20Hindu%20deity%20Varuna%20(a%20sculpture%20from%20the%20museum%E2%80%99s%20own%20collection)%20is%20brought%20in%20relation%20to%20Greek%20Triton%20(Roman%20Neptune)%20to%20convey%20the%20human%20desire%20to%20control%20turbulent%20sea%20storms%20and%20navigate%20across%20vast%20oceanic%20waters.%20Similarly%2C%20depictions%20of%20the%20%E2%80%98desirable%E2%80%99%20and%20the%20%E2%80%98ideal%E2%80%99%20female%20form%20continue%20to%20be%20popular%20across%20cultures.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EA%20delicate%20image%20of%20Greek%20Aphrodite%20(Roman%20Venus%2C)%20the%20goddess%20of%20love%20and%20passion%20from%20the%20Berlin%20Museum%2C%20is%20drawn%20into%20comparison%20with%20similar%20female%20forms%2C%20such%20as%20apsaras%20and%20yakshinis%2C%20which%20adorn%20the%20walls%20of%20the%20Hindu%20temple.%20The%20museum%20has%20chosen%20to%20focus%20on%20the%20Didarganj%20Yakshini%2C%20particularly%20to%20highlight%20the%20feminine%20ideal%20from%20ancient%20India.%20Even%20though%20this%20prized%20icon%2C%20dated%20to%20the%203rd%20century%20BCE%2C%20now%20preserved%20in%20the%20Bihar%20Museum%2C%20Patna%2C%20is%20not%20physically%20present%20in%20the%20exhibition%2C%20its%20detailed%20description%20and%20images%20convey%20the%20idea.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESimilarly%2C%20a%20sandstone%20image%20of%20Hapy%20(goddess%20of%20annual%20flooding%20of%20the%20Nile)%20from%20the%20British%20Museum%20is%20set%20in%20dialogue%20with%20one%20of%20the%20earliest%20depictions%20of%20the%20Ganga%20carrying%20a%20water%20pot%2C%20made%20of%20terracotta%20now%20in%20the%20National%20Museum%2C%20Delhi.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThrough%20this%20unique%20curatorial%20approach%2C%20by%20tapping%20into%20collections%20of%20other%20museums%2C%20even%20though%20the%20objects%20cannot%20be%20physically%20brought%20in%2C%20the%20exhibition%20makes%20a%20noteworthy%20effort%20to%20make%20the%20museum%20visitors%20aware%20of%20these%20iconic%20masterpieces%20and%20highlight%20India%E2%80%99s%20artistic%20repository.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20exhibition%20also%20underscores%20both%20the%20complex%20philosophical%20underpinnings%20of%20Indian%20sculptures%20as%20well%20as%20their%20ritual%20purpose.%20Visitors%20are%20invited%20to%20explore%20the%20museum%E2%80%99s%20vast%20and%20permanent%20collection%20of%20Hindu%2C%20Buddhist%20and%20Jain%20religious%20images%2C%20thus%20extending%20the%20exhibition%20beyond%20the%20rotunda%20and%20into%20its%20galleries.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20recent%20years%2C%20the%20museum%20has%20made%20consistent%20efforts%20to%20re-examine%20its%20historic%20collection%20of%20ancient%20sculptures%20and%20present%20these%20with%20a%20fresh%20narrative%20and%20state%20of%20the%20art%20display.%20The%20object%20labels%20in%20the%20Hindu%20gallery%20have%20been%20carefully%20crafted%20moving%20beyond%20the%20basic%20information%20of%20nomenclature%2C%20chronology%20and%20material%20of%20fabrication%20to%20address%20questions%20of%20geographical%20provenance%20and%20architectural%20and%20ritual%20placement%20in%20the%20Hindu%20temple.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20984px)%2061vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2045vw%2C%20600px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F03121700%2Fimage-1800.png%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22641%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F03121700%2Fimage-1800.png%20641w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F03121700%2Fimage-1800-249x300.png%20249w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-695505%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22772%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EA%20view%20of%20the%20Hindu%20arts%20gallery%20at%20CSMVS.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFor%20instance%2C%20in%20a%20city%20guided%20by%20the%20rhythms%20of%20the%20annual%20Ganpati%20festival%2C%20what%20is%20the%20significance%20of%20a%207th%20century%2C%20stone%20image%20of%20Ganpati%20from%20Gujarat%20for%20a%20common%20museum%20visitor.%20Moving%20away%20from%20the%20textual%20interpretation%20of%20sculptures%2C%20as%20has%20been%20the%20norm%2C%20the%20gallery%20ope